# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-new-zealand
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Australia has named a senior Australian rules football team, known as the All-Australian team since 1947.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] This team, however has never officially played an international Australian rules football match.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] This is primarily because the sport is played professionally in Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] It has previously sent teams to play against Ireland's amateur Gaelic Athletic Association in the hybrid code of International Rules Football as the Australia international rules football team (this article is not about that team).
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] While the All-Australian team does not compete, the **AFL National Academy** (known simply as the "AFL Academy") is a national team composed of underage (under-19) players.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In the past it has played annual matches against New Zealand, though currently it competes only against semi-professional state league teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] History has shown that more than two thirds of Academy players go on to professional careers at senior level in the Australian Football League.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In addition, sides representing Indigenous Australia have competed internationally, including the Indigenous All-Stars against Papua New Guinea and the Flying Boomerangs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Australia remains undefeated, although Papua New Guinea came within two goals of a historic win at Football Park in 1978 and New Zealand within a goal at Wellington Stadium in 2014.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Early in the spread of football codes across the globe, international tours and tests played a pivotal role.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] However, from the sport's early days, although plans were tabled for tours to England, various leagues had lacked the resources and organisation to send tours overseas.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] H C A Harrison "Father of Australian Football" was a supporter of the idea of international matches against England and New Zealand, and in London in 1884, pitched playing under compromise rules, however the idea was rejected.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The idea was made more difficult as prior to the Federation of Australia the Australian colonies could still not reach a consensus on the idea of fielding a national side.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Some teams did however tour and played matches in Australia against Australian sides, notably in 1888 and 1889, the British & Irish Lions and New Zealand Native team played matches against clubs in Australia but no recognised international tests.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] These tours were conditional on Australian leagues playing some matches under rugby rules to keep the competition fair.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Generally games were won by the teams playing their own code and this led to the perception that the codes were by now too dissimilar for such matches to continue.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Unlike the football codes with less players sending squads of 18 to 22 players on international tours would prove to be an expensive exercise and sharing the costs across multiple colonies would prove much more difficult than, for example, New South Wales sending a national rugby team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] It wasn't until the formation of the national body, the Australasian Football Council in 1906 that the opportunity presented itself for funding and organisation for a national team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] However representatives of the two strongest leagues, the Victorian Football League and South Australian Football League, in an effort to protect their primacy in Australia, lobbied the council to form a strict policy discouraging the game from being played overseas.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Through the council they allocated all funds to interstate representation, and none to international representation.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The policy was boosted by a wave of post-Federation Australian nationalism.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In 1906 the council's official policy became "one flag, one destiny, one football game" and chose to play all matches under an Australian flag, on Australian turf with an Australian manufactured ball.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The first request for international tour came in 1906 from Australian rules football in South Africa, the AFC therefore replied that if it wanted to play against Australia, it would have to send a team to Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] This was to become the council's default stance.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] New Zealand had only one representative on the council, and faced opposition from most of the Australian colonies.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Though it was given permission to send a side to the 1908 Melbourne Carnival (which defeated Queensland and New South Wales) the AFC never fielded a national team against them.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Subsequent calls from overseas for Australia to send teams to the United States (1909), New Zealand (1910), Japan (1910) and Canada (1912) were all rejected by the AFC.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] For a country with less than a thousand players, USA's junior athletes proved highly competitive against the Australian sides.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In 1912, Canada sent a junior touring side to Australia, however the tour was not recognised by the AFC and as such no composite Australian representative side was fielded against them.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] With the rapid growth in the United States, the AFC's delegate from Western Australia strongly argued for sanctioned tours to both the United States and Canada, however the governing body elected not to.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The result was that most competitions outside Australia went into permanent recess by the end of the 1920s.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In contrast, the top leagues in Australia were going professional and a widening gap in interstate representative matches would make it almost impossible for other countries to compete.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] A promotional tour, known as the Australian Football World Tour, took place in 1967, with matches played in Ireland, the United Kingdom, and the United States, though without any local players no international matches of Australian rules were played.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] This resulted in the first International Rules matches played between Australia and a touring County Meath Gaelic football team, Meath being the reigning All-Ireland senior football champions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The national side was known as the "Galahs".
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Ireland would maintain the VFL's primary international focus (especially given its ongoing Irish Experiment recruiting initiative) through to the 21st century.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Though it was not officially endorsed by the AFC, support for the idea was continued by the VFL/AFL and later Australian Amateur Football Council.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In the 1960s and 1970s, Australian rules was unexpectedly booming in the Pacific in Papua New Guinea and Nauru.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] While Nauru had been soundly defeated by PNG it was considered far too small a nation to field a competitive side against Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Papua New Guinea however with tens of thousands of players to draw from, had a fast moving and hard hitting side that was competitive against some of the VFL's strongest clubs, and was extremely determined to compete against Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In 1977 a Victorian U17 team travelled to Port Moresby and were almost defeated.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] PNG persevered and in 1978 sent a team to Adelaide, and in a historic match came close to beating Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] However the Australian National Football Council withdrew its promise to admit PNG as a voting member, along with senior funding and plans to tour Papua New Guinea and the local competitions soon collapsed.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] This was in part due to the country's national sporting body withdrawing funding due to a lack of international competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In turn this also left Australia with no opponent.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] When the International Australian Football Council was formed in 1995 one of its aims was to 'establish and promote an official World Cup of Australian Football'.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The initial proposal was for similar eligibility criteria to other football codes which would mean that it could draw the significant pool of Australians born overseas or with a parent or grandparent from the country they chose to represent.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] This would in turn reduce the logistical and financial burden on overseas clubs who would send their best players to top up the squads.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] At the time it was thought that 2008, being the 150th anniversary of the game, was the appropriate date.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The idea of Australia eventually entering an amateur side was first proposed.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In 1999 a proposal was received from the New Zealand Australian Football League (NZAFL), suggesting that the World Cup be brought forward to 2002.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] An approach was then made to the national body, the AFL, asking for their support in staging the event.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The AFL agreed on the basis that the event was renamed the "International Cup", that an Australian side would not compete and that there be strict eligibility criteria to exclude Australian players.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In 2004, the AFL formed its own International Policy, pushed for the dissolution of the IAFC to became formally recognised as the world governing body for the sport.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] It took the International Cup over and put it under its development arm.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The idea of an Australian team, even a development or amateur one, participating in the tournament was dismissed.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Australia did not compete internationally at any recognised level until the AFL Commission in 1998 formed a 10-year partnership with the Australian Sports Commission (ASC) and the Australian Institute of Sport (AIS), the AIS-AFL Academy, with national sports funding.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The AIS junior development funding was contingent on international competition, which the AFL was able to satisfy through a junior International Rules Series against Ireland.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The AIS funded scholarships to 30 17 year old players for a year based on their football performance as a 16 year old, their positive attitude to education and schooling and potential to play at professional AFL level.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] However, with the GAA cancelling both the senior and junior series in 2006, the AFL had to find another opponent in order to continue to receive national sports funding. which it sought to capitalise on burgeoning Australian investment in Australian rules football in South Africa.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Following some highly unevenly matched contests, the gap between the two countries drew comments from AFL CEO Andrew Demetriou the South Africans would be better suited to playing a game with a round ball (referring to International Rules but possibly also soccer).
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] In 2011, the program expanded to include two squads however the AFL abandoned the South African program and sent a side on tour to Europe to play against a combined side.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The Australian Institute of Sport withdrew from the partnership in 2013 to focus on Olympics recognised sports.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The National Australia Bank extended its Australian Football sponsorship to the AFL Academy to fill the gap left by the AIS.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The AFL's partnership in New Zealand with Wellington Regional Stadium helped fill the gap left by the AIS and it began playing its development team against an open aged NZ sides in 2012.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Competing as the AFL Academy (or Australia U17) an annual series of tours was established against New Zealand as part of a junior development pathway with AFL New Zealand.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The AFL also sent tours to Europe in 2013 and 2014 to compete against a combined AFL Europe side known as the European Legion.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The AFL also set up International Combines in Europe and New Zealand from which some of the athletes participated as the Academy's opposition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] New Zealand matches were later extended to include women's matches however COVID-19 pandemic put international matches on hold.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] At the end of 2018, the AFL put an end to overseas tours for its AFL Academy, which meant that international sides would once again require to travel to Australia to compete.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Unable to secure nationals sports funding the AFL also restructured the AFL Academy into state-based academies, diverting funding intended for overseas tours into academies featuring its clubs in developing states of New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Since 2019 the state-based academies have formed the basis of the AFL National Academy teams for boys and girls, made up of primarily players in the under-18 age bracket.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] The boys team have played once-a-year fixtures against teams from the Victorian Football League and South Australian National Football League, while the girls have competed against combined under-23 state teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-academy] Both teams undertake regular training and high-development camps, as well as partake in yearly formal matches against opposition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] AFL New Zealand currently has 30,000 Registered Players, although this is refuted, as it would mean that each of the clubs in the country has 1,875 players per team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] Australian rules football is a sport played in New Zealand rapidly gaining popularity.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] AFL New Zealand co-ordinate the national team, who have competed in the Australian Football International Cup and crowned international champions in 2005.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] Since 2012 the national side has played against the National Australian Under 17 team (NAB AFL Academy).
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] The first game was won convincingly by the AFL Academy by 91 points.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] 2013 saw the Australians win by 44 points and in 2014 it took a goal in the final minutes to win their third straight game by only 4 points.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] NZAFL selects a team of the best Australian-based players with NZ heritage.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] This team includes some AFL legends including Simon Black (Brisbane Lions AFL) and Wayne Schwass – (Sydney Swans AFL).
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] The AFLNZ National Provincial Championships were an annual tournament between the regional leagues comprising the New Zealand Australian Football League.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] The first of the current incarnation of the NPC was held on 25 and 26 September 2004 in Christchurch.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] Since 2016 AFL New Zealand runs a 4 team 8 round men's national competition as part of its high performance programme similar to the AFL Academy club pathway in Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] Players are recruited via a national draft from throughout the country.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] Matches are played at North Harbour Stadium outer oval in Auckland and QE2 Park Christchurch.
[src:afl-new-zealand/afl-new-zealand] A women's national league was established in 2019, with only Waitākere having a full women's roster, an opponent, the Lions was drafted from female players across the country.
[src:afl-new-zealand/athletics-new-zealand] The organisation was founded in 1887 as the New Zealand Amateur Athletic Association (NZAAA).
[src:afl-new-zealand/athletics-new-zealand] The first national championships were held the following year in 1888.
[src:afl-new-zealand/athletics-new-zealand] There are 11 regional athletics associations supporting 179 clubs with approximately 22,000 registered members including athletes, coaches and volunteers.
[src:afl-new-zealand/athletics-new-zealand] ANZ maintains the New Zealand records in athletics.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The **Auckland Australian Football League** which began in 1974, is an amateur Australian rules football competition in Auckland, New Zealand currently consisting of 6 clubs and is one of the leagues governed by AFL New Zealand.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The league has a men's competition and affiliated women's competition known as Auckland Women's AFL featuring some of the same clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The competition runs from September to December to avoid clashes with the rugby football season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] An earlier league which existed in Auckland from 1904 until the outbreak of World War I was also known, for a time, as the Auckland Australian Football League.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The Auckland Australian Football Association (AAFA) was founded by former Australian professional player Terry Gay in 1974, North Shore Tigers were one of the foundation clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] Four teams were playing in 1988 and it shifted its season to spring.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] It was renamed Auckland Australian Football League (AAFL) in 1990.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] In 2012 the AAFL established a 2nd Division for less competitive clubs however this lasted only one year before all clubs were to play in first division.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] Season 2021 was cancelled due to COVID-19 pandemic restrictions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The competition resumed in 2022 where the North Shore Tigers became the first team to go undefeated for an entire season, going 12-0 including finals..
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] This record has been added to in subsequent years with the Tigers going on to remain undefeated through the 2023 and 2024 seasons currently sitting at 44 games undefeated.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] Location map of current clubs in the league.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The 'Auckland Football Association (under Victorian rules)' was formed at a meeting at Foresters' Hall, Newton on 28 April 1904.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The initial subscription rate was 2s 6d, and forty members were enrolled at that meeting.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] At the 1906 AGM, the name was changed to 'The Australian Football League of Auckland' in order to differentiate the league from Rugby Union and Association (soccer) football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] After several active seasons which were covered in some depth in the local papers, the league went into decline around the end of the decade due to the departure of a number of the Australian players back home.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] In 1912 the senior competition was put on hold due to the lack of players, with only a junior competition continuing.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] A number of the players in the league were immigrants from the southern Australian states.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] Regular mention was made in the newspaper reports of the arrival of these gentlemen and their intentions to play football in Auckland.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The inaugural president of the league in 1904 was a Mr McNamara.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] He was supported by a large committee that included 5 vice presidents; Messrs Hale, McKeon, Walsh, Kneebone and McVeigh.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] At the 1905 AGM, Dr Tracy Inglis was elected president, a position he held for a number of years.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The league had a number of prominent people involved during it existence.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] Patrons of the league in 1905 included politicians George Fowlds and F E Baume.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] The new league's first game was a scratch match held on 30 April on the outer Domain.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] Several rounds of practice matches followed prior to the start of the competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/auckland-australian-football-league] By the end of the 1904 season Austral and Imperial were "on a level footing", with Austral taking the honours, 29 to 18, in the final which was held at the Domain Cricket Ground.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The Australasia County Board of the Gaelic Athletic Association (GAA), or **Australasian GAA**, or **Gaelic Football & Hurling Association of Australasia** is one of the county boards of the GAA outside Ireland, and is responsible for Gaelic games all across Australasia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] It is also responsible for Australasian inter-state matches, primarily conducted in an annual weeklong tournament.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The association is made up of the Australian state associations of New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Western Australia, and the New Zealand associations of Wellington and Canterbury.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In 1840, in Sydney's Hyde Park, games of Hurling and Football were played by Irishmen.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] During Adelaide's St Patrick's Day celebrations in 1843, families native to Ireland played a football game "in genuine Irish style".
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The game started at 2pm and was played in honour of Saint Patrick.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In 1846, there was controversy when an Irish gathering sought to "play an old Irish game" in Sydney's Hyde Park.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In 1859, there were mentions of arrangements to celebrate "Gaelic games" in Geelong.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In 1864, an article in the Freeman's Journal of Sydney wrote about celebrating a holiday by renewing "some of our old national customs, our old manly games and exercises, hurling [and] football".
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In 1887, the Freeman's Journal in Sydney, a Catholic publication, printed the GAA's revised rules for Irish football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In December 1860, a hurling match was played in the state of Victoria, an event which attracted a large attendance of Irishmen.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The first Australian GAA was formed in Auckland, New Zealand, in 1953.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] Victoria's GAA was formed in 1956, followed by New South Wales.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] This was followed in 1963 by the formation of a South Australian association and associations in Western Australia and Queensland soon after.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The first interstate championships in both codes were played between NSW, Victoria and South Australia in 1971.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In Sydney in 1974 representatives of state associations met and agreed to form the Gaelic Athletic Association of Australia to administer and promote Gaelic football and hurling on a national level.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] Subsequently, the Gaelic Athletic Association of Australia joined with the New Zealand associations of Auckland and Wellington to form the Gaelic Athletic Association of Australasia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The Australasian Championships, commonly referred to as the Australasian Games, are a week-long tournament staged annually in September/October each year and hosted by one of the member state associations.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] Tournaments typically feature all codes, with hurling played for the first time as part of a championships held in New Zealand in Wellington in 2015, and camogie added full-time in 2012.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In most circumstances, there is only one side per state per code, but when numbers are low in a code (typically hurling) or in the number of states entered (usually when the tournament is in Western Australia or New Zealand) exceptions to this are made.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The tournament format in each code varies year-to-year depending on the number of entries, but generally involves either a round-robin or pool play format with either two semi-finals or one semi-final with the top qualifier progressing directly to the final.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] A final is played in each code to determine the champion for the year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] Each association is permitted to name a panel of 22 players in each code for the championships, with unlimited interchange rather than the more traditional substitution rule used for each match.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] In recent years, a 'visa' rule was introduced to encourage states to develop their own players.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] This rule limits the number of players any state may select in any code who are not either Australians or New Zealanders, or have obtained residency in either country.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australasia-gaa] The Australasia Ladies' football team have won three Women's World Cup competitions (the tournament does not include Irish sides) in 2000, 2002 and 2005.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] The **World Backgammon Federation** (**WBGF**), formerly the **European Backgammon Federation** (**EUBGF**) until 2018, is the international body established to support and promote the table game of backgammon worldwide.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] Their functions include the regulation of competition rules worldwide, the assessment and ranking of players and the establishment of regional governing bodies, and hosting tournaments internationally.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] Among their objectives is the legal recognition of backgammon as a mind sport at national and international levels.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] As of 2026 WBGF has over 40 member nations.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] WBGF has member nations from Europe, Americas, Asia Pacific, Middle East and Africa.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] Some of these member nations include Austria, Argentina, UAE, Turkiye, UK and Japan.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] WBGF and WBGF's member nations both host tournaments.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] The tournaments hosted by WBGF's member nations can be local or international.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] These tournaments are hosted under WBGF's statutes.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] WBGF's most prestigious tournaments as of 2026 are the WBGF World Teams Championship, WBGF World Women's Team Championship and WBGF World Individual Championship.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australia-new-zealand-backgammon-federation] According to the statutes board members are elected and elections are made in General Assemblies of the World Backgammon Federation.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The **Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup** or simply the **IC**) was a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] It was the biggest international tournament in the sport that is open to all nations (it is not called a World Cup as Australia does not compete due to the presence of the professional AFL competition and an abundance of semi-professional leagues).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] More than 26 nations have participated and the competition has expanded into multiple pools and both men and women's divisions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] At the time of the last tournament in 2017, the sport had a record 170,744 registered players outside Australia (upwards of 23 per cent of total registered players worldwide) growing at a rate of 25 per cent per annum (as compared to an Australian participation growth rate of 10 per cent).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The inaugural 2002 tournament was organised by the first world governing body, the International Australian Football Council.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] With the AFL Commission assuming control over the game internationally, since 2005 it has been run by the Australian Football League (AFL)'s game development arm.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The IC Grand Final of each men's tournament has been held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to an AFL premiership season match.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Though it is run under the banner of the AFL Commission, the AFL's official Laws of the Game are not used, an Amateurs variation is instead applied, acknowledging the primarily amateur composition of the competition and that players are not paid for participating.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Although the competition has grown, its status has remained low for more than two decades, and the arrangement has been criticised due to the focus on domestic competition; the AFL's commitment to fund and promote the sport internationally has also been questioned.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The Commission stated that it would "continue to review its ability" to stage the tournament in future.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Competition scheduling discourages it as a standalone spectator event with few pool matches played at stadiums; matches are generally played on weekdays during business hours and rarely with access to ticketed admission, allocated seating, or covered areas.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The event and matches receive very little if any promotion.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Despite the limited accessibility for spectators some regional matches played on weekends have attracted significant attendances, with the current attendance record of 5,000 at The Showgrounds, Wangaratta.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Eligibility rules are very strict compared those of other international competitions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Generally speaking, players must be citizens of the country they represent and have lived there through roughly middle school and high school ages (when most players usually learn the key skills required).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] IC criteria ensures that expatriate Australians, Australians with overseas ancestry and those who moved to Australia at a young age are ineligible to compete (with the exception of the short-lived and unsuccessful women's Indigenous & Multicultural (OzIM) composite amateurs team in 2011).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] These rules, combined with professional contracts and limited pathways for players, typically preclude professional players from participating.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there is a per-team cap on players registered with Australian clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Despite this, since the 2011 competition, the cup has featured a number of AFL-listed internationals and rookies; however, these players had to first negotiate a release from their AFL/AFLW contracts before being nominated and are not paid for their appearances.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] To date, three players have played senior matches at the highest level in both competitions – the amateur IC and professional club competition: Hewago Oea (Papua New Guinea/AFL), Laura Duryea (Ireland/AFLW) and Clara Fitzpatrick (Ireland/AFLW).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Likewise, the tournament forms a pathway for international players to the AFL, with numerous players having been rookie-listed by AFL clubs after their performances in the competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] However, in 1999 a proposal was received from the New Zealand Australian Football League (NZAFL), suggesting that the World Cup be brought forward to 2002.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] This was accepted by the council and, following visits to many countries, IAFC public relations officer Brian Clarke drafted a discussion paper and draft regulations for circulation to the various national bodies.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] An approach was then made to the AFL, asking for their support in staging the event.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL agreed on the basis that the event was renamed the "International Cup".
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] An organising committee, chaired by Ed Biggs and including AFL and IAFC representatives, was then appointed.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] All matches were played in Melbourne at mainly second tier suburban and Victorian Football League home grounds.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Ireland defeated Papua New Guinea in the final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The second cup in 2005 was run by the AFL's Game Development arm, as the IAFC had been dissolved.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] It saw the addition of Spain but the withdrawal of Denmark and Nauru for financial reasons.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] While most of the venues were similar to 2002, it was the first tournament to have matches held outside Melbourne, with the Victorian city of Wangaratta hosting one of the later rounds.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand won their first championship.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The third cup in 2008 saw a record sixteen nations with China, India, Sweden, Finland and a combined Israel-Palestine side (known as the Peres Peace Team) debuting.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Tonga entered as a seventeenth team, but as they were unable to commit to the full draw they played a series of multicultural exhibition matches against *Team Asia* and *Team Africa*, sides drawn from Melbourne's migrant communities.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Like the previous cup, the 2008 event had some matches played outside of Melbourne with the western Victorian city of Warrnambool billed as the co-host and other games being held in Geelong and at Royal Park, Melbourne, featured as a primary venue in subsequent Cups.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea, which had advanced to the Grand Final in both previous tournaments, won its first title.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The fourth tournament, the 2011 Australian Football International Cup, was the first to play matches outside of Victoria, with Sydney being billed as co-host.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Blacktown International Sports Park and suburban grounds hosted some of the early round matches and a historic first international at ANZ Stadium between the USA and South Africa played as a curtain raiser to a Sydney Swans AFL match.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] A record eighteen nations competed, and a women's division was competed for alongside the men's competition for the first time.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] It was the first tournament to feature a side from Australia, the OzIM women's team, composed of amateur indigenous and multicultural players, however the team did not perform well.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] It was also the first tournament to be split into divisions, seeded from an opening round lighting-style format similar to the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The tournament saw the addition of teams from Fiji (who went on to take out Men's Division 2), France and Timor-Leste.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Tonga, who had previously withdrawn, also competed but Finland and Samoa did not send teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the title in both men's and women's divisions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The 2014 Australian Football International Cup saw a significant increase in international and media interest.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The Israel-Palestine combine was no longer represented and Denmark announced a return to its domestic game development policy.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Indonesia and Pakistan made debuts in their place.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] As in previous tournaments, one of the rounds was played outside of Melbourne, with matches played at suburban grounds in Melbourne along with regional matches at Bendigo, Ballarat and Geelong.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] South Africa, Fiji and France were the standout improvers.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea regained their title in the men's, winning their second title in five tries, while Sweden finished top of Division 2.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Fiji and Tonga debuted in the women's division and the United States and Canada both fielded two women's teams making a record seven teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Canada achieved a historic first ever title in the women's, defeating Ireland at Punt Road Oval.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 Australian Football International Cup once again featured eighteen men's teams, including debutante Sri Lanka, reflecting the game's growth in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] European teams were finding travel difficult, with northern European nations Finland, Denmark and Sweden (Sweden having competed in both the 2016 Europe Championships and also Denmark in the 2016 and 2017 EU Cups) pulling out, though Croatia and Germany made solid debuts.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's divisions were determined prior to the tournament instead of preliminary matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Two themed rounds were featured: the School round, where matches were played at Victorian schools, and the Community round, as in 2014 where matches were played at suburban grounds in Melbourne and Geelong.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea won back-to-back men's titles, Croatia won a historic first Division 2 title.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In the women's, Great Britain, Pakistan and the European Crusaders joined a record field of eight teams with no nations fielding more than one team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Ireland regained its women's title over Canada at Docklands Stadium in the first women's grand final match played as an AFL curtain raiser.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The 2020 International Cup was scheduled for 21 July – 8 August in Sunshine Coast, Queensland.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] It was initially postponed until 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic before being cancelled altogether in 2021.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Prior to the tournament several changes had been announced.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Criteria were made more strict, reducing the number of Australian based players allowed to compete.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand announced the planned entry of its first women's team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL had, for the first time, announced capping the men's competition to sixteen teams and the women's to eight.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In August 2021, the AFL announced that the IC would return in 2023 to align with its original three-year schedule but did not announce the host.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it was postponing the International Cup until 2024 citing "significant investment required from the AFL to host the event".
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] However, on 24 July 2023, the AFL announced that, in lieu of the International Cup, that it would be sponsoring three regional events in 2024: the Trans-Atlantic Cup, the Asia Cup, and the Pacific Cup to be hosted by an international affiliate.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL gave no indication as to when the International Cup would be resumed, however indicated that these are the only AFL sanctioned international tournaments since 2017 (effectively nullifying the 2019 and 2022 AFL Europe Championship).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] AFL Canada was announced as host of the Transatlantic Cup to be held at the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto on August 2–11, The Maroochydore Multi Sports Complex on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland was announced as the host of the Pacific Cup on 14–24 November.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Thanh Long Sports Center in Vietnam would host the Asia Cup at in Ho Chi Minh City from December 6–8 in 2024.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL announced strict selection criteria, that each player must hold citizenship for the country that they are representing and must have played in from a local competition in that country.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] "W/D" = Withdrew from the tournament without playing a match after officially committing to field a side that year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Prior to 2011, all men's teams competed in one division.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Sorted by winning percentage, with draws counted as half a win, half a loss, and percentage (points for/points against x 100).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Table includes finals and has been adjusted to reflect this.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] ^ Table includes finals and has been adjusted to reflect this.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Since the 2011 Australian Football International Cup the Men's competition has been split into two Divisions, with the format differing from each past edition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In 2011 and 2014, the divisional lineup was decided by a preliminary competition that involved all eighteen teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In 2017, the divisions were pre determined prior to the tournament, with ten teams playing in Division 1 and eight playing in Division 2.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In 2014, Division Two was decided by ladder position.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] As of the cancelled 2020 tournament there is no formal system in place for qualification of participating sides and countries are extended open invitations to send sides.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL had, for the first time, announced capping the men's competition to sixteen teams and the women's to eight; however no system for qualification has been proposed.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] While there are now established regional tournaments in Europe, Asia and North America performance in these tournaments does formally affect seedings for the International Cup.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The tournament is geared towards development of the sport outside Australia and as such player eligibility rules are much more strict than those of other international football competitions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Generally speaking players must be a citizen of the country they represent and have lived there through roughly middle school and high school ages (so that is usually where they learned to play).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] IC criteria ensures that expatriate Australians, Australians with overseas ancestry and those who moved to Australia at a young age are ineligible to compete (with the exception of the women's OzIM team, which is composed of indigenous and multicultural Australians).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] These rules, combined with professional contracts and limited pathways for players typically precludes professional players from participating and players wishing to participate must negotiate their own release from their AFL/AFLW contracts before nominating.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In addition there is a per team cap on players registered with Australian clubs which countries teams from stacking their teams with talent developed in Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] This limit was initially set to twelve, however with the increasing number of international players participating in Australian competitions and an increasing number of players learning the game outside Australia, this was later reduced to eight.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The following AFL and AFLW listed international players have previously represented their country at the IC.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] No senior AFL players on contracts have yet been released to play in the International Cup, like most amateur representative competitions, this is primarily due to the risk of injury.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] However clubs will sometimes make exclusions to allow the participation of lower paid rookies, international scholarship players and AFL Women's players in the amateur tournament.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Tournament best and fairests have been named since 2005.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In addition, each nation typically nominates their best and fairest player.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] A World (formerly All-International) Team is selected from the best players (similarly to the All-Australian Team selection in the AFL).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Prior to 2008, field positions and captaincy positions were not nominated.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Captaincies have not been nominated since 2014.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The IC has maintained a low media profile for more than two decades.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Apart from the Grand Final which is played as a curtain raiser, matches not scheduled for stadiums are free entry and are generally played midday and mid-week prohibiting it as a spectator event, though some regional matches have been played on weekends.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The 2002 tournament was video recorded and posted on the IAFC website though there were no live broadcasts.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The United States Australian Football League also provided video coverage and recorded a documentary on its participation.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The 2005 tournament attracted some coverage from Fox Sports including a Grand Final replay on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel, though matches were not broadcast.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Some community radio and television stations in Victoria also provided limited coverage and *World Footy News* provided score updates.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL began posting videos of the 2008 tournament on its website along with editorial posts after the matches were played.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL failed to secure a broadcast partner for the 2011 tournament, instead adding delayed highlights to their online video service.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] For the 2014 tournament the AFL included live streaming for the first time and the tournament attracted media interest from outside Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] For the 2017 tournament the AFL partnered with Internet service YouTube to provide live streaming of the three rounds held at Royal Park and the two Grand Finals.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The USAFL, AFL Canada, *World Footy News*, and the Eastern Football League provided supplementary coverage of the school and community rounds.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] IC coverage was not included in the AFL's record breaking 2.5 billion broadcasting deal in 2015 or contract negotiations in 2019 for the 2020 extension, though Kayo will stream AFLW matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The inaugural IAFC tournament was held in the game's spiritual home of Melbourne, with some games at suburban stadiums around the city.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] With the AFL headquartered in Melbourne, all events have been hosted in Victoria, Australia with regional matches in Warrnambool (2008), Wangaratta (2005), the exception being matches scheduled for Sydney, New South Wales in 2011.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The West Australian Football League expressed an interest in bidding for the 2008 cup to go to Perth, Western Australia however the AFL did not open up hosting to bidders and the tournament was held in Victoria instead.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The cancelled 2020 tournament was the first time in the history of the event that the AFL opened up to bidders as part of a closed bidding process.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Among newly introduced criteria was that the grounds must meet the AFL's Preferred Facility Guidelines at Regional level to qualify.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] These include requirements for the ground dimensions and surface, staff facilities, lighting and accessibility.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The guidelines are mainly aimed at providing AFL staff with maximum amenity, there are no requirements for spectator seating, viewing mounds and a covered area under which spectators can stand are deemed sufficient for calculating ground capacity.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The guidelines, combined with the requirement to have at least two main fields meeting this requirement in close proximity, has significantly raised the barrier to entry for hosting the tournament.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] At the end of 2019, the AFL announced that it had selected the Sunshine Coast bid which would have seen the event hosted outside of Melbourne and Victoria for the first time (not counting the 2011 event which saw some secondary matches played in Western Sydney).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] As part of the Queensland bid, the Grand Finals would be played at the Brisbane Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to a Brisbane Lions AFL premiership match.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Queensland remained the successful bidder when the tournament was postponed until 2021.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] However following the cancellation of the 2020 tournament, no announcement was made as to whether the Queensland bid would be retained.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it would be continuing discussions with the winning Sunshine Coast bid.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL (video game series) by Melbourne game developer Wicked Witch Software has featured selectable teams, including player names, from the IC.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In particular, AFL Evolution and AFL Evolution 2 let players play the entire IC17 tournament, but at AFL-standard stadiums from around Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The IC has been a development pathway for several players who have been rookie listed or received an international scholarship with professional AFL clubs or clubs from semi-professional competitions throughout Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] The first player to this pathway was Laura Corrigan who made an AFLW debut in 2016 following a 2011 senior appearance for Ireland.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] In 2022, the first male player, Hewago Oea made his debut in the AFL following a 2017 senior appearance for Papua New Guinea.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] IC's potential as a pathway was first promoted by Kevin Sheedy while coaching at the Essendon Football Club, following the 2005 cup he invited Japanese IC players Michito Sakaki and Tsuyoshi Kase to train and play with the club's pre-season team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Though Essendon did not recruit Sakaki, he received an invitation to AFL Draft Camp and the exposure was a catalyst for the Wodonga Raiders club contracting him to play semi-professionally in the strong Ovens & Murray league in 2006.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] For older international players, the IC is one of the only options other than moving to Australia and moving up the semi-professional competition pathway, to be noticed by recruiters and rookie listed to the AFL or AFLW.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Unlike the AFL International Combine open-aged pathway, the IC is accessible to amateurs from a much broader international area and tests their gameplay and game sense, rather than just their athletic attributes.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] For underaged international players the IC provides an alternative pathway and the opportunity to prove their ability to compete at a high senior level.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Currently only New Zealand competes against the AFL Academy (Australia's best junior players) (though South Africa has in the past).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] Since the first IC has been a major pathway for Papua New Guineans to play professionally (even with affiliations to Queensland in the National Championships).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] IC players from other countries to have been recruited to play professionally include Padraig Lucey (Ireland) at Geelong Football Club, Joe Baker-Thomas (New Zealand) at St Kilda Football Club, Yoshi Harris (Nauru) at GWS Giants, and Kendra Heil (Canada) at Collingwood.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-international-cup] All of these players were rookie listed shortly following outstanding performances in an IC tournament.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The **Australian Football League** (**AFL**) is the pre-eminent professional competition of Australian rules football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] It was originally named the **Victorian Football League** (**VFL**) and was founded in 1896 as a breakaway competition from the Victorian Football Association (VFA), with its inaugural season in 1897.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] It changed its name to Australian Football League in 1990 after expanding its competition to other Australian states in the 1980s.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL publishes its *Laws of Australian football*, which are used, with variations, by other Australian rules football organisations.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL competition currently consists of 18 teams spread over Australia's five mainland states, with Tasmania to join the league as its 19th team in 2028.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] AFL premiership season matches have been played in all states and mainland territories, as well as in New Zealand and China to expand its audience.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] As of 2024 the AFL is the richest Australian football and overall sports league in Australia by revenue and the 16th richest sports league in the world by revenue.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL premiership season currently consists of a 24-match regular (or home-and-away) season, which runs from March to September.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The team with the best record at the end of the home-and-away season is awarded the minor premiership; the top ten teams then play off in a five-round finals series, culminating in the AFL Grand Final, which is normally held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground each year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The grand final winners are termed the premiers, the most important team prizes for which are the premiership cup and flag.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Carlton, Collingwood and Essendon are the joint-most successful clubs in the competition, having each won 16 premierships.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Brisbane Lions are the reigning premiers, having won the 2025 AFL Grand Final.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Several of the AFL's current member clubs date back to the origins of Australian football and were instrumental in establishing the sport's popularity and the AFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The oldest club is Melbourne Football Club, which wrote the first laws of the code, and Geelong, which date back to 1858 and 1859 respectively, while Melbourne University, also founded in 1859, is also one of the oldest clubs to have later participated in the competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Victorian Football Association (VFA) was established in 1877 and quickly went on to become Victoria's football competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] During the 1890s, an off-field power struggle occurred between the VFA's stronger and weaker clubs, the former seeking greater administrative control commensurate with their relative financial contribution to the game.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] This came to a head in 1896 when it was proposed that gate profits, which were always lower in matches involving the weaker clubs, be shared equally among all teams in the VFA.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The remaining VFA clubs—Footscray, North Melbourne, Port Melbourne, Richmond and Williamstown—were given the opportunity to compete as junior sides at a level beneath the VFL but rejected the offer and remained for the 1897 VFA season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFL's inaugural season occurred in 1897.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Although the VFL and the VFA continued to compete for spectator interest for many years, the VFL quickly established itself as the premier competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1908, the league expanded to ten teams, with Richmond crossing from the VFA and University Football Club from the Metropolitan Junior Football Association.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Professionalism began from the 1911 season, with clubs permitted to pay players beyond the reimbursement of expenses for the first time.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The premiers of the Victorian Football League and the premiers of the South Australian Football League met in playoff matches for the Championship of Australia beginning in 1888, with a 3-game playoff between South Melbourne from the VFL and Norwood from the SAFA.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Matches where then held sporadically during the 1890s as single game playoffs and then annually from 1907 until 1914 (except 1912).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] South Australian clubs won 8 of the 11 titles, with Port Adelaide being the most successful, having won four titles in 1890, 1910, 1913 and 1914.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The majority of the matches were held in South Australia at Adelaide Oval.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Following the outbreak of World War 1 the Championship playoff ceased and wasn't revived until 1968.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1916, district football was introduced, meaning new players from metropolitan Melbourne were allocated to clubs based on residential address.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1925, the VFL expanded from nine teams to twelve, with Footscray, Hawthorn and North Melbourne each crossing from the VFA.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] North Melbourne and Hawthorn remained very weak in the VFL for a very long period.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Although North Melbourne would become the first of the 1925 expansion sides to reach a grand final in 1950, initially it was Footscray that adapted to the VFL with the most ease of the three clubs and by 1928 were well off the bottom of the ladder.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] From 1927 to 1930, Collingwood became the first, and as of 2025, the only VFL/AFL team to win four successive premierships.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1952, the VFL hosted a national day, when all six matches were played outside Melbourne.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Matches were played at the Sydney Cricket Ground, Brisbane Exhibition Ground, North Hobart Oval, Albury Sports Ground and Victorian country towns Yallourn and Euroa.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Footscray became the first of the 1925 expansion teams to win the premiership in 1954.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Melbourne became a powerhouse during the 1950s and early 1960s under coach Norm Smith and star player Ron Barassi.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The club contested seven consecutive grand finals from 1954 to 1960, winning five premierships, including three in a row from 1955 to 1957.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The became the only club to win the minor premiership 6 times in a row from 1955 to 1960.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Television coverage for the VFL commenced in 1957 with direct telecasts of the final quarter permitted.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] At first, several channels competed through broadcasting different games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] However, when the VFL found that television coverage had reduced crowds, it decided that no television coverage was to be allowed for 1960.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1961 television replays in Melbourne were introduced although direct telecasts were rarely permitted, compared with the rest of Australia where live telecasts happened every Saturday afternoon.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1959, the VFL planned the first purpose-built mega-stadium, VFL Park (later known as Waverley Park), to give it some independence from the Melbourne Cricket Club, which managed the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] VFL Park was planned to hold 155,000 spectators, which would have made it one of the largest stadiums in the world – although it would ultimately be built with a capacity of 78,000.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Land for the stadium was purchased at Mulgrave, then farmland but predicted to be near the demographic centre of Melbourne's population.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFL premiership trophy was first awarded in addition to a pennant flag in 1959; essentially the same trophy design has been in use since.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In the 1960s, television coverage began to have a huge impact on the VFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Spectators hurried home from games to watch replays and many former players took up positions as commentators on pre-game preview programs and post-game review programs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] There were also several attempts at variety programs featuring VFL players, who generally succeeded in demonstrating that their skills were limited to the football ground.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFL played the first of a series of exhibition matches in 1962 in an effort to lift the international profile of the league.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1967, district football was expanded throughout all of Victoria, clubs now allocated a country zone in addition to their metropolitan districts.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The 1970 season saw the opening of VFL Park, with the inaugural match being played between Geelong and Fitzroy, on 18 April 1970.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Construction work was carried out at the stadium as the 1970s progressed, culminating in the building of the now heritage listed Sir Kenneth Luke Stand.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Queen Elizabeth II, was a guest at the game and formally opened the stadium to the public.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1976, the National Football League, which was the peak national administrative body of Australian rules football at the time, established the NFL Night Series to succeed the Championship of Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Night Series was played concurrently with the premiership season and was contested among twelve clubs from the VFL, SANFL and WAFL, invited based on their finishing positions from the previous year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The event was mostly played on Tuesday nights, with night games at Norwood Oval in Adelaide and all games were televised live in colour on Channel 9, which opened up unprecedented revenue streams from television rights and sponsorship opportunities for the sport.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The NFL began plans to expand its Night Series to incorporate more teams from the VFL, SANFL and WAFL, as well as state representative teams from other states.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In November 1976, the VFL announced that it was withdrawing from the NFL's competition, having arranged more substantial television and sponsorship deals for its own, rival night competition for 1977 to be based in Melbourne and feature only the VFL clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Light towers were erected at VFL Park specifically for the event.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFL established a proprietary limited company called Australian Football Championships Pty Ltd in 1978 to run its night competition and offered shareholdings to the other state leagues in an attempt to lure other states into the competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] For the three years from 1977 until 1979, the NFL and VFL night competitions were run separately as rival night competitions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1978, the Tasmanian representative team competed in both the NFL and VFL night competitions but all SANFL and WAFL clubs and the minor states teams remained in the NFL Night Series.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1979, the WAFL clubs and the New South Wales and A.C.T. representative teams defected from the NFL Night Series and joined the VFL's night competition, leaving the NFL Night Series mostly composed of SANFL teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The NFL Night Series was not revived in 1980 and the SANFL clubs joined the VFL's night competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1982, the size of the competition was reduced and, thereafter, only the top two or three teams from the SANFL and WAFL, as well as the winner of the minor states' annual carnival were invited.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1987, the night competition reverted to include only the VFL teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The competition was pushed earlier into the year, with the final played on 28 April.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The following season, the competition did not overlap with the day premiership season at all and became entirely a pre-season competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The night competition is generally considered to be of equivalent importance as the pre-season competition and the VFL Night Series (1956–1971) and records relating to the three competitions are often combined.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] With the number of players recruited from country leagues increasing, the wealthier VFL clubs were gaining an advantage that metropolitan zoning and the Coulter law (salary cap) restricting player payments had prevented in the past.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Country zoning was introduced in the late 1960s and while it pushed Essendon and Geelong from the top of the ladder, it created severe inequality during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Between 1972 and 1987, only six of the league's twelve clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Hawthorn, North Melbourne and Richmond – played in grand finals.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The 1980s was a period of significant structural change in Australian football around the country.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFL was dominant among the Australian football leagues around the country in terms of overall attendance, interest and money and began to look towards expanding its influence directly into other states.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFL and its top clubs were asserting their financial power to recruit top players from interstate.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The resulting rising cost pressures drove the VFL's weaker clubs into dire financial situations.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The South Melbourne Swans became the first VFL team to relocate interstate.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The South Melbourne Football Club was deeply indebted, including to the VFL which took over the club's Swans team and moved the team's home games to Sydney in 1982 and renamed the team the Sydney Swans the following year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Under the private ownership of Dr Geoffrey Edelsten during the mid-1980s, the Sydney Swans became successful on-field.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Moving the Swans team to Sydney effectively shifted the debts of a Melbourne club onto Australian football in Sydney and re-directed support and finance to the Swans team to the detriment of existing Australian Football clubs and league competitions in Sydney.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] However, the Swans team attracted new prominence and supporters for the sport.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Despite becoming successful on the field, a succession of owners and transfer to its supporter "members", the Sydney Swans remain indebted to the AFL and subject to its veto control and reversion rights in what became a model for the AFL control of teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Throughout the 1980s, approaches were made by SANFL and WAFL clubs to enter the VFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Of particular note were approaches by the East Perth Royals in 1980, the Norwood Redlegs in 1986 and 1988, and an East–South Fremantle merger proposal in 1987.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] None of these attempts were successful despite Norwood trying again in 1990 and 1994.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1986, the West Australian Football League and Queensland Australian Football League were awarded licences to field expansion teams in the VFL, leading to the establishment of the clubs in Brisbane and Perth (Brisbane Bears and West Coast Eagles), who both joined the league in 1987.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] These expansion team licences were awarded on payment of multimillion-dollar fees which were not required of the existing VFL clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1989 financial troubles nearly forced Footscray and Fitzroy to merge but fees paid by the Brisbane Bears and West Coast Eagles, propped up the struggling VFL sides.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The 1980s first saw new regular timeslots for VFL matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] VFL matches had previously been played on Saturday afternoons but Sydney began playing its home matches on Sunday afternoons and North Melbourne pioneered playing matches on Friday night.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] These have since become regular timeslots for all teams.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The first national draft was introduced in 1986 and a salary cap was introduced in 1987.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] District football within Victoria was discontinued around the same time.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The league was renamed the Australian Football League in 1990 to reflect its national composition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1990 the AFLPA, the players union, signed its first Collective Bargaining Agreement (CBA) with the league which outlined wages and conditions in what was becoming a sole source of income for players who had previously had part-time or full-time jobs outside of football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Midway through 1990, the SANFL's most successful club, Port Adelaide, made a bid for an AFL licence.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In response, the SANFL gained an injunction via Glenelg and Norwood against Port Adelaide, allowing it time to establish a composite South Australian team called the Adelaide Crows, which was awarded the licence and joined the league in 1991 as the fourth non-Victorian club.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The same year saw the West Coast Eagles become the first non-Victorian club to reach the grand final, which was won by Hawthorn (the same year saw the Brisbane Bears win the reserves premiership).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Eagles would then win the premiership in 1992 and 1994.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1994, Fremantle obtained an AFL licence and joined the AFL in 1995, becoming the fifth non-Victorian club, and the second from Western Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The VFA took over the Victorian Football League name in 1996.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1996 several Victorian clubs were in severe financial difficulties, most notably Fitzroy and Hawthorn.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Hawthorn proposed to merge with Melbourne to form the Melbourne Hawks but the merger ultimately fell through and both teams continued as separate entities.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Fitzroy, however, was too weak to continue by itself.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The club nearly merged with North Melbourne to form the Fitzroy-North Melbourne Kangaroos but the other clubs voted against it.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1994 Port Adelaide was awarded an AFL licence but could not enter until a Victorian team had folded or merged.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] At the end of 1996 Fitzroy played its last match and merged with Brisbane to form the Brisbane Lions.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] This allowed Port Adelaide to enter the AFL for the 1997 season as the sixth and only pre-existing non Victorian club.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Through the 1990s there was a significant trend of Melbourne-based teams abandoning the use of their small (20,000–30,000 capacity) suburban venues for home matches in favour of the MCG and VFL Park, which have and had larger seating capacities.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The 1990s saw the last matches played at Windy Hill (Essendon), Moorabbin Oval (St Kilda), Western Oval (Footscray) and Victoria Park (Collingwood) and saw Princes Park abandoned by its long-term co-tenant, Hawthorn.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The transition to the use of only two venues in Melbourne was ultimately completed in 2005 when Carlton abandoned the use of Princes Park.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1999, the league sold VFL Park and used the funds in a joint venture to begin construction of a brand-new stadium situated at Melbourne's Docklands.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Representative state football came to an end, with the last State of Origin match held in 1999.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In the late 2000s, the AFL looked to establish a permanent presence in Gold Coast, Queensland, which was fast-developing as a major population centre.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] North Melbourne, which was in financial difficulty and had played a few home games on the Gold Coast in previous years, was offered significant subsidies to relocate to the Gold Coast but declined.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL then began work to establish a club on the Gold Coast as a new expansion team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Early in 2008, a meeting held by the AFL discussed having two new teams enter the AFL competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In March 2008, the AFL won the support of the league's 16 club presidents to establish sides on the Gold Coast and in Western Sydney.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Gold Coast Suns were established and joined the AFL in 2011 as the 17th team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Greater Western Sydney Giants, representing both Western Sydney and Canberra, were then established and entered the league as the 18th team in 2012.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] On 25 April 2013 the Westpac Stadium in Wellington, New Zealand hosted the first ever Australian Football League game played for premiership points outside Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The night game between St Kilda and Sydney was played in front of a crowd of 22,183 on Anzac Day to honour the Anzac bond between the two countries.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] A national women's league comprising a subset of AFL clubs began in 2017.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Thirteen AFL clubs placed bids to participate in the women's competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Eight clubs – Adelaide, Brisbane Lions, Carlton, Collingwood, Fremantle, Greater Western Sydney, Melbourne and the Western Bulldogs – were granted licences to participate in the inaugural season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Six clubs joined the league in the coming years; Geelong and North Melbourne entered the competition in 2019, while Gold Coast, Richmond, St Kilda and West Coast made their debut in 2020.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The remaining four clubs—Essendon, Hawthorn, Port Adelaide and Sydney— entered AFL Women's in the seventh season in 2022.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] On 14 May 2017, Port Adelaide and the Gold Coast played the first-ever AFL match for premiership points in Shanghai, China, attracting a crowd of 10,114 at Jiangwan Stadium.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide won the game by 72 points.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 2020, the AFL season was severely disrupted by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The first round of matches was played in front of no crowds due to the pandemic, before the season was suspended on 22 March due to health concerns and strict government regulations on non-essential travel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] After nearly two months of planning with the assistance of state governments and health officials, the season resumed on 11 June, with the length of the season reduced from 22 matches per team to 17 matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The grand final was played in October at The Gabba in Brisbane, the first time it was held outside of Victoria since the creation of the league due to the spiking cases in that state.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The pandemic caused the league to lose out on up to $400 million in anticipated revenue and also precipitated a 20% cut in industry jobs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The 2021 grand final was played in September at Perth Stadium in Perth because an ongoing COVID-19 lockdown prevented the match from being played with spectators at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne, Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] It was the first grand final played in Perth and the second consecutive grand final to be played outside Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The event set a new attendance record for Australian rules football in Western Australia, eclipsing the previous record set in 2018 despite not featuring any WA-based teams and being played during the COVID pandemic.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL operates on a single table system, with no divisions and conferences, nor promotion and relegation from other leagues.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The league was founded as the Victorian Football League (VFL) in 1897, comprising eight teams only based in the state of Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Over the next century, a series of expansions, a relocation, a merger and a club withdrawal saw the league's teams expand to the 18 teams there are today.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 1990, the national nature of the competition resulted in the name change to the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The current 18 teams are based across five states of Australia; the majority (ten) still remain in Victoria, nine of which are located in the Melbourne metropolitan area.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The states of New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia and Western Australia have two teams each, and a team from Tasmania will enter the competition in 2028.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Australian Capital Territory and Northern Territory are the only mainland territories not to have AFL clubs, although the Greater Western Sydney Giants have a contract to play at least three home games in Canberra until 2032, while at least two games per year are played in Darwin.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Since the league commenced in 1897 as the VFL, only one club, University, has withdrawn from the competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] It last competed in 1914 and withdrew because, as an amateur club, it was unable to remain competitive in a time when player payments were becoming common; the club still competes to this day in the Victorian Amateur Football Association (VAFA).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Two other clubs, Fitzroy and the Brisbane Bears, merged in 1996 to form the Brisbane Lions: however, after coming out of financial administration in 1998, Fitzroy resumed its playing operations in 2009 and competes in the VAFA.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Throughout the history of the VFL/AFL to 2023, there have been 50 grounds used.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The largest-capacity ground in use is the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG), which has a capacity of over 100,000 people and hosts the grand final each year (see AFL Grand Final location debate).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The MCG is shared by six teams as a home ground, while the other grounds used as home venues by multiple teams are Docklands Stadium in Melbourne (five teams), Adelaide Oval in Adelaide (two teams) and Perth Stadium in Perth (two teams).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL has had exclusive ownership of Docklands Stadium (commercially known as Marvel Stadium) since late 2016.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Prior to the expansion of the competition, most grounds were located in suburban Melbourne, with Princes Park, Victoria Park, the Junction Oval, Waverley Park and the Lake Oval each having hosted over 700 games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] However, since the introduction of a national competition, each state and territory of Australia has hosted AFL games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] On 25 April 2013 (Anzac Day), a match took place between St Kilda and Sydney at Wellington Regional Stadium in Wellington, New Zealand, being the first AFL match played outside Australia for premiership points.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Below are the venues that are hosting AFL matches during the 2025 season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] AFL players are drawn from a number of sources; however, most players enter the league through the AFL draft, held at the end of each season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] A small number of players have converted from other sports, or been recruited internationally.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Prior to the nationalisation of the competition, a zoning system was in place.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] At the end of the season, the best 22 players and coach from across the competition are selected in the All-Australian team.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL has tight controls over the player lists of each club.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Changes to playing lists are permitted only in the off-season: clubs can trade players during a trade period which follows each season and recruit new players through the three AFL drafts, the national draft, the pre-season draft and the rookie draft, which take place after the trade period.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] A mid-year draft was conducted between 1990 and 1993.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The national draft is the primary method of recruiting new players and has been used since 1986.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The draft order is based on reverse-finishing position from the previous year but selections can be traded.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Free agency player movements have only been permitted since the 2012/13 offseason, previously having been rejected by the AFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] As part of the AFL's enhanced equalisation policies, in 2014 the league announced an increase of the TPP for the **2015** and **2016** seasons.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] TPP increased an additional $150,000 per club in 2015 above previously contracted amounts, increasing from $9.92m to $10.07m in 2015 and $10.22m to $10.37m in 2016.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The salary cap was set at $1.25 million for 1987–1989 as per VFL agreement, with the salary floor set at 90% of the cap or $1.125 million; the salary floor was increased to 92.5% of the cap in 2001 and 95% of the cap for 2013 due to increased revenues.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Both the salary cap and salary floor has increased substantially since the competition was rebranded as the AFL in 1990.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Salaries of draft selections are fixed for two years.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Salaries for senior players are not normally released to the public, though the average AFL player salary at the conclusion of the 2012 season was $251,559 and the top few players can expect to earn up to and above $1,000,000 a year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Upon successfully trading to the Sydney Swans in 2013, marquee player Lance Franklin signed a 9-year contract with the club, reportedly worth over $10 million and resulting in subsequent payments of $1.8 million annually in consecutive seasons.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Total Player Earnings (TPE) – or total amount of revenue spent on reimbursement of AFL listed players – at the conclusion of the 2012 season was $173.7 million, up by 13 per cent from $153.7 million in 2011.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In June 2017, the AFL and AFL Players Association agreed to a new CBA deal which resulted in a 20% increase in players' salaries.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The six-year deal, which began in 2017 and ends in 2022 means that the average player wage rises from $309,000 to $371,000 and the player salary cap from $10.37m to $12.45m.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 2022, the final year of the agreement, the average player wage will be $389,000 with a salary cap of $13.54m.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The breaches of the salary cap and salary floor regulations outlined by the AFL are: exceeding the TPP; falling below the salary floor; not informing the AFL of payments; late or incorrect lodgement or loss of documents; or engaging in draft tampering.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Penalties include fines of up to triple the amount involved ($10,000 for each document late or incorrect lodged or lost), forfeiture of draft picks and/or deduction of premiership points.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The most significant breach of the salary cap was that of the Carlton Football Club in the early 2000s.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] There were 801 players on AFL club senior, veteran, rookie and international lists in 2011, including players from every state and mainland territory of Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] As of 2014, there were 68 Indigenous Australian players on AFL club lists, comprising approximately 9% of the overall playing population.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] There were 12 players recruited from outside Australia on AFL lists in 2011, including 10 from Ireland, all converts from Gaelic football drafted as part of the Irish Experiment and one each from the United States and Canada.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] There were also another five overseas-born players who emigrated to Australia at an early age on AFL lists.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] An international rookie list and international scholarship list were introduced in 2006.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The international rookie list includes up to two players between the ages of 15 and 23 who are not Australian citizens.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] These players may remain on this list for up to three years before they must be transferred to the senior or rookie list.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] For the first year, payments made to international-rookie-listed players fell outside the salary cap.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The international scholarship list gives AFL clubs the option of recruiting up to eight players from outside Australia (other than Ireland).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Irish players are required to either be placed on clubs' senior or rookie lists.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] At the beginning of 2011, there were 14 international scholarship players.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Of the 121 multicultural players, more than half have one parent from Anglophone countries, mainly the United Kingdom, Ireland and New Zealand.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] From 1988 until 2013, the AFL ran a pre-season competition that finished prior to the commencement of the premiership season, which served as both warm-up matches for the season and as a stand-alone competition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] It was mostly contested as a four-week knock out tournament but the format changed after the expansion of the league beyond sixteen clubs in 2011 and has frequently been used to trial rule changes.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 2014, the competition format was abandoned and practice matches are now played under the sponsored name **Marsh Community Series**.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] This consists of all 18 clubs playing two matches each, which are played on some weekdays and weekends, throughout February and early March.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL home-and-away season at present lasts for 25 rounds, starting in early March and ending in late August.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] As of the 2026 AFL season, each team plays 23 matches, consisting of 11 home games, 11 away games, 1 neutral game, and two byes.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Teams receive four premiership points for a win and two premiership points for a draw.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Ladder finishing positions are based on the number of premiership points won.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] "Percentage", calculated as the ratio of points scored to points conceded throughout the season, is used as a tie-breaker when teams finish with equal premiership points.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Further tie-breakers, if required, are the premiership points accumulated in head-to-head matches between the tied teams and then the percentage earned in such matches, with a final tie-breaker being a random drawing of lots.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Several teams also play against each other at set times each year, with the most prominent of these being when Collingwood play Essendon in the annual Anzac Day clash at the MCG.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Other prominent matches include the King's Birthday match between Collingwood and Melbourne and the Easter Monday clash between Geelong and Hawthorn.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] As of November 2023 the men's league had no plans to introduce a Pride Round in the men's game, although the AFLW had established their pride round in 2021.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] There are separate trophies for matches between several clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Perhaps the most well-known of the themed rounds is the **Indigenous Round**.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 2007, following the success of the Dreamtime at the 'G matches in 2005 and 2006, the AFL nominated a specific Indigenous Round (round 9), which has become an annual event in which the Dreamtime at the 'G match takes centre stage on a Saturday night.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The success of the annual match, which now usually features crowds in excess of 80,000, led to the two clubs agreeing to cement the match arrangement for an additional decade in May 2016.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 2016, the round was named after Sir Doug Nicholls, the only VFL player to have been knighted and who served as a state governor (of South Australia).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The round is now officially named the **Sir Doug Nicholls Round**.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Each year, each player in all 18 clubs wears a specially commissioned artwork by an Indigenous artist on their guernsey, and some clubs rebrand with Indigenous club names in place of their regular names for the duration.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] As introduced in the 2026 AFL Season, only the top 6 are locked into finals whilst places 7-10 are to play in a 'Wildcard Round' as outlined in the new AFL final ten system.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Places 7 and 10, 8 and 9 play to finalise the top 8 teams who will progress into week 2 of the finals.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The finals series is played throughout September, culminating in a grand final to determine the premiers.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The grand final is traditionally played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on the afternoon of the last Saturday in September.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The winning team receives a silver premiership cup, a navy blue premiership flag – a new one of each is manufactured each year – and is recorded on the perpetual E.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The flag has been presented since the league began and is traditionally unfurled at the team's first home game of the following season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The Wilson Shield, named after Edwin Lionel Wilson, was first awarded after the 1929 premiership.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The premiership cup was first introduced in 1959 and is manufactured annually by Cash's International at their metalworks in Frankston, Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Additionally, each player in the grand final–winning team receives a premiership medallion.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Other independent best and fairest awards are presented by different football and media organisations.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] To celebrate the 100th season of the VFL/AFL, the "AFL Team of the Century" was named in 1996.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Jack Elder was declared the *Umpire of the Century* to coincide with the Team of the Century.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Since the naming of this side, most AFL clubs have nominated their own teams of the century.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] An Indigenous Team of the Century was also selected in 2005, featuring the best Aboriginal players of the previous 100 years from both the VFL/AFL and other state leagues.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] State representation football in the AFL initially ended in 1999.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The concept has been revived twice since then in 2008 and 2020 when a Victorian state team took on all stars teams (in 2008 against *The Dream Team* and in 2020 against the *All Stars*).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] VFL players first represented the Victoria representative team in 1897 regardless of their state of origin.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL assumed control of interstate football in 1993 and coordinated an annual State of Origin series typically held during a mid-season bye round.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] However, after the 1999 series, the AFL declared the concept of interstate football "on hold", citing club unwillingness to release star players and a lack of public interest.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Indeed, the 1999 series, where Victoria defeated South Australia by 54 points, was played in wet conditions in front of a crowd of 26,063, whereas 10 years earlier, the same match-up with a plethora of star players attracted a crowd of 91,960.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] The AFL shifted its focus of representative football to the International Rules Series, where at the time in the late 1990s, drew a greater television revenue.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] A once-off representative match, known as the AFL Hall of Fame Tribute Match, was played in 2008 to celebrate the 150th anniversary of the sport between a team of players of Victorian origin and a team of players of interstate origin (the "Dream Team"), which was won by Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] In 2020, the AFL hosted a special one-off State of Origin match, with the money raised from the event going towards affected bushfire communities.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] On 28 February, the game took place at Marvel Stadium, with Victoria defeating an All-Stars team and Dustin Martin being declared best on ground.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Since 1996, some past AFL players participated and helped with the promotion of the E.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p01] Whitten Legends Game, although this, too, was put on indefinite hiatus following the 2019 edition.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] On 17 October 2010, AFL clubs Melbourne Demons and Brisbane Lions played an exhibition game in front of 7,000 people at the Jiangwan Sports Center in Shanghai.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] This was the first professional AFL game to be played in China.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Since then, AFL premiership matches have been played in New Zealand and China, and the competition developed some interest in North America amidst the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL has garnered increased interest in Ireland due to the introduction of the International Rules Series played between an AFL-picked Australian Team (sourced entirely from All-Australian players since 2004) and Ireland international rules football team beginning from 1984.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The series is organised under the auspices of the AFL and the Gaelic Athletic Association.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The game itself is a hybrid sport, consisting of rules from both Australian football and Gaelic football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The series provides the only outlet for AFL players to represent their nation.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] This series encouraged young Irish footballers switching code to join AFL teams because, whilst the Gaelic Football is strictly amateur, the AFL is fully professional, thus players can make a living out of playing AFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] However, some Irish players fail to make the grade into the very competitive AFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] This also paved the way for extended news coverage and increased broadcasting in the United Kingdom and Ireland.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Around the same time that the inaugural International Rules Series commenced, Australian Football Hall of Fame Legend Ron Barassi launched the Irish experiment, which scouted and recruited dozens of Irishmen (usually Gaelic footballers) with potential for crossing over to playing in the AFL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] This resulted in successful recruitmant and training of Australian Hall of Famer Jim Stynes among other successful players.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL is governed by directors known as the AFL Commission.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The commission chairman is Richard Goyder, who took over from Mike Fitzpatrick on 4 April 2017.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In addition to administering the national competition, the AFL is heavily involved in promoting and developing the sport in Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] It provides funds for local leagues and in conjunction with local clubs, administers the Auskick program for young boys and girls.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL also plays a leading role in developing the game outside Australia, with projects to develop the game at junior level in other countries (e.g.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] South Africa) and by supporting affiliated competitions around the world (See Australian football around the world).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The players of the AFL are represented by the AFL Players Association, the coaches are represented by the AFL Coaches Association, the umpires are represented by the AFL Umpires Association and the related media employees are represented by the Australian Football Media Association.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL was the best-attended sporting league in Australia in 2012.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] According to market research, the AFL is the second-most-watched sporting event in Australia, behind cricket.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Currently, broadcast rights for the AFL are shared between the Seven Network (free-to-air), Foxtel (pay TV) and Kayo Sports (internet).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In 2019, a record 1,057,572 people were members of an AFL club.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Excluding the grand final (which is exclusive to Seven Network in Australia), 54% of viewers watched using the paid services of Foxtel or Kayo in 2022, while 46% watched the Seven Network's free-to-air broadcasts.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] 1 Finals total and Finals average include grand final crowds.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] 3 Capacity reduced due to MCG refurbishment.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] 5 Crowd for the grand final replay, played one week after the drawn grand final.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] 6 Attendance reduced due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] 7 Capacity reduced due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] 8 Waverley Park was used for the Grand Final due to the Great Southern Stand at the MCG being under construction.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] AFL matches are currently broadcast in Australia by the free-to-air Seven Network and subscription television provider Foxtel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The current deal was announced in September 2022 and covered the inclusive 2025–2031 seasons.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The Seven Network broadcasts an average of three-and-a-half games a round; Friday Night, Saturday Night, Sunday Afternoon and any Thursday or Monday Night matches that may occur throughout the year.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Channel Seven also airs the AFL Finals Series and the AFL Grand Final.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Foxtel broadcasts every match through their Fox Footy channels, including simulcasts from the Seven Network except for the grand final, which is aired exclusively on Channel Seven.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Foxtel also has the rights to air rounds on their internet protocol television platform titled Foxtel Now, as well as via the sports streaming service Kayo.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The 1957 VFL season was the first broadcast after the commencement of television in Australia (introduced in 1956 to coincide with the Melbourne Olympic Games).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] During the late 1950s and 1960s, all Melbourne stations (ABV2, HSV7, GTV9 and, after it commenced in 1965, ATV0/ATV10) broadcast some games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] However, in the late 1950s and early 1960s, the VFL was concerned that direct telecasts may affect attendances and stations were only permitted to telecast a delayed replay of the last quarter of games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] From 1974 until 1986, the Seven Network and the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) were given exclusive rights to VFL/AFL games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The only year Seven did not telecast games was 1987 when the rights were bought by Broadcom, which on-sold the rights to the ABC in Victoria.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Seven regained the rights in 1988 and also exclusive rights.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] With the launch of subscription television in Australia, AFL match coverage commenced on cable television.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Optus Vision bid for and won exclusive pay-TV rights from 1996 to 2001, screening coverage on its own 24-hour AFL channel, branded *Sports AFL* in Brisbane, Sydney and Melbourne (where available).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The Sports AFL channel was later closed due to financial issues and relaunched in March 1999 as C7 Sport by the Seven Network with AFL match coverage also transferred to the new channel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] C7 Sport became available in regional areas not in the Foxtel or Optus Vision licence area via Austar soon after the re-launch.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL coverage was not available through Foxtel at this time as the Seven Network and Foxtel disagreed on the cost of carrying the C7 channel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] These issues regarding C7 and AFL broadcasting rights evolved into a court case between not just the Seven Network and News Limited but Seven against the owners of the Nine Network and Network Ten in the years that followed.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] On 25 January 2001, the Seven Network's main rivals, the Kerry Packer led Nine Network, Network Ten and pay-TV's Foxtel set up a consortium which bid $500 million for the right to broadcast the 2002–2006 seasons inclusive.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Seven had purchased a guaranteed right to make the last bid in 1995, but decided not to outbid their rivals.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The games were split between the networks, with Nine screening Friday Night Football, a live Sunday afternoon game in the east and, if needed, a doubleheader for WA and SA, Ten screened a Saturday afternoon and a Saturday night match, with the remaining three matches shown on Foxtel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Foxtel set up its own version of a dedicated AFL-only channel, the Fox Footy Channel, which showed every game on replay during the week, as well as many news, talkback and general interest shows related to Australian rules football.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] After lengthy negotiations, Foxtel agreed to be a broadcast partner and showed four live matches each week, although no longer on a dedicated AFL channel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Seven took back the Friday night match and only one game on Sunday, while Ten retained showing two matches on Saturdays.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Foxtel showed two games on Saturday and two on Sunday, including a late afternoon or twilight game.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The 2012–2016 rights were bought by Seven, Foxtel and Telstra for $1.25 billion, the biggest sport telecasting deal in Australian history at the time.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] As part of the deal, Foxtel would show all home-and-away AFL matches live, as well as all Finals bar the grand final, via the resurrected Fox Footy.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Telstra would broadcast all matches via mobile and Seven would broadcast three live matches (Friday night, Saturday night and Sunday afternoon) and one delayed match (Saturday afternoon).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Seven also had the option to on-sell one game a week to either Nine or Ten; this did not happen.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The 2017–2022 rights were re-bought by Seven, Foxtel and Telstra for $2.5 billion, besting the previous deal to become the most lucrative in Australian history at the time.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Under the terms of the deal, Seven broadcasts at least three live matches per round as well as all Finals matches, whilst Foxtel broadcasts (or simulcasts Seven's feed) all nine matches per round, as well as all Finals bar the grand final, which is exclusively broadcast by Seven.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Telstra continues to maintain exclusive mobile broadcast rights to all matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] There are some variations in broadcasting dependent on the relevant state or territory.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The agreement with Seven, Foxtel and Telstra was extended in 2020 by two years to include the 2023 and 2024 seasons.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In 2021 Telstra's AFL streaming service, AFL Live Pass, was removed and replaced with access to Kayo, run by Hubbl (then called Streamotion), a wholly owned subsidiary of Foxtel.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The 2025–2031 rights were re-bought by Seven, Foxtel and Telstra for $4.5 billion, once again besting the previous deal to become the most lucrative in Australian history.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] As part of the deal, Seven would show three-and-a-half games a week on average during the home-and-away season, as well as all Finals and the Brownlow Medal.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] This includes Thursday Night games for the first 15 rounds of each season and streaming rights to all matches they broadcast via 7+.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Fox Footy would continue to show every home-and-away game and every final live bar the Grand Final via Foxtel and Kayo, as well as select matches on Binge.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] All Foxtel matches will have Fox Footy commentary, including simulcasts of Channel Seven matches, and Saturday matches will be exclusive to Fox Footy for the first fifteen rounds bar any marquee matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] These arrangements differ outside of Victoria, where every local team's match will be broadcast on free-to-air, albeit with Saturday matches on delay for the first eight rounds.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Prior to the start of the 2025 season, the deal was altered such that Fox Footy's Saturday exclusivity in Victoria was extended to the entire home and away season.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In exchange, the AFL would schedule Thursday Night Football for almost the entire season, allowing Seven to broadcast the same number of games.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Historically AFL broadcasts in other countries have varied.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In late 1979, the brand new ESPN cable network signed the league's first international TV contract.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Coverage began with the 1980 season with matches airing on late Friday and Saturday nights, sometimes live but usually one or two week tape delayed to up to 2.5 million subscribers.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] At the time, reports indicated ESPN paid the VFL nearly $100,000 (the VFL's Australian TV rights deal at the time was just $600,000).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The 1983 VFL Grand Final was the first time in history that the Grand Final was broadcast live into the US.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Coverage continued on ESPN until 1986, when the sport was dropped after which it was not broadcast in the US for over a decade.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] New Zealand was the second country which held broadcast rights in 1980, with highlight packages with the Grand Final going live into the country.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In the early 1990s, American regional sports network Prime Sports (unrelated to the Australian regional television network) aired Seven's weekly highlight show as well as the grand final.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Some other English speaking countries have shown the game, however, it has been since 2008 that channels in other countries began televising matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] From 1998 to 2006 games were broadcast in the United States by the Fox Sports World network.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In 2007, after the record domestic television rights deal, the AFL secured an additional bonus: greater international television rights and increase exposure to overseas markets, including a five-year deal with Setanta Sports and new deals with other overseas pay-TV networks.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The deal ended early in 2009 when Setanta stopped broadcasting into Great Britain.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Additionally, AFL games can be shown in Irish pubs and sport pubs by request in Bangkok.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Thai's broadcasting rights is under ABC Asia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The first broadcast of a VFL game was by 3AR in 1923, the year that licensed broadcasting commenced in Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The first commentator was Wallace (Jumbo) Shallard, a former Geelong player who went on to have a long and respected career in print and broadcast media.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The VFL/AFL has been broadcast every year since then by the ABC and (since 1927) by various commercial stations.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The saturation period was the early 1960s when seven of the eight extant radio stations (3AR, 3UZ, 3DB, 3KZ, 3AW, 3XY and 3AK) broadcast VFL games each week, as well as broadcasts of Geelong games by local station 3GL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] (At this time, the only alternative that radio listeners had to listen to the football on a Saturday afternoon were the classical music and fine arts programs that were broadcast by 3LO).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The vast majority of radio broadcasting is done in English.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] However, ethnic radio stations broadcast the AFL in a variety of languages, including Arabic, Chinese, Greek, Hindi and Spanish.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Many also broadcast in Indigenous languages, as the sport is very popular among Indigenous Australians.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL's contracted internet/mobile broadcast partner is Telstra.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL also provides exclusive broadband content, including streaming video for international fans, via its website.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Telstra also hosts the websites of all the 18 AFL clubs.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] However, the website is frequently derided by users for its convoluted information architecture and bloated presentation.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Since 2012, Telstra has broadcast live matches over its Next G mobile network for a pay-per-view or season fee.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Since 2019, Kayo has broadcast every game, except the Grand Final, live.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In Feb 2021, Telstra terminated the AFL Live Pass service, replacing it with access to Kayo at a discount for Telstra customers.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Streaming rights outside of Australia for full games are currently held by the Watch AFL subscription service operated by Fox Sports Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL's contracted print media partner is News Corp Australia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The *AFL Record* is a match-day magazine published by the AFL and is read by around 225,000 people each week.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL sells memberships that entitle subscribers to reserve seats for matches at Docklands Stadium and the Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] AFL members also receive priority access to finals.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Three levels of memberships are offered, bronze, silver and full (gold).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Only full members have guaranteed access to preliminary and grand final matches.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Bronze members are restricted to fewer matches at the MCG only.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL has declared its support for LGBTIQ community, organising pride games in June 2017.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In September 2017, in conjunction with the Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey, the AFL modified its logo sign at Docklands Stadium support of same-sex marriage (however, only for 24 hours).
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In August 2025, Mitch Brown came out publicly as bisexual, becoming the AFL's first openly LGBTQ past or present player.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Before his coming out, the AFL was the only major professional men's sport league worldwide to have never had an openly LGBTQ past or present player.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Brown revealed that the weight of hiding his sexuality had taken its toll on his AFL career, where homophobic insults and conversations were commonplace on and off the field.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] AFL CEO Gillon McLachlan had previously stated that "the pressure and the weight of being... the first AFL player who comes out and plays as an out, gay man" was too much of a burden for the known gay players in the league to come out.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Former players and officials suggested that a cause for the previous lack of openly queer players was a culture of homophobia and silence within the AFL, with former captain and ally Bob Murphy recalling shamefully his offhanded use of homophobic slurs as a young player.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] Homophobic language remains a problem at games with legal recommendations from the Australian Sports Commission made in 2000 to address this still not implemented.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In 2015 the Sydney Swans played a pre-season game at Drummoyne Oval against Fremantle Dockers as a Pride Game.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] This became an annual event, which has grown from year to year in strength and support.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The club has an official LGBTQIA+ supporter group, Rainbow Swans.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In September 2017 the AFL ruled that Hannah Mouncey, a transgender woman, was ineligible for selection in the 2018 AFLW draft.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] There has been some opposition to the AFL's decision.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] It has been suggested that the men's game could do more to promote inclusivity, as has been done in the AFLW.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFLW Pride Round has been officially held since 2021, although there were individual AFLW clubs who had played Pride games since 2018.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The intention of the Pride Round is to celebrate gender diversity, promote inclusion for LGBTIQA+ players, and to help stamp out homophobia.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] As of November 2023 the men's league had no plans to introduce a Pride Round in the men's game.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The AFL supported the creation of an Indigenous Voice to Parliament, ahead of the 2023 Australian Indigenous Voice referendum.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In 2023, a group of former players began a class-action lawsuit against the league regarding the concussions that they suffered while playing.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] The case is similar to the cases including cases against the NFL and the NHL.
[src:afl-new-zealand/australian-football-league-p02] In 2023, former female umpire Libby Toovey took the league to the Fair Work Commission, claiming that she was dismissed after uncovering systemic abuse of female umpires by the league.
